In[9]:
def clean_currency(value):
    if pd.isna(value) or value is np.nan:
        return np.nan
    
    clean_str = re.sub(r'[^\d.]', '', str(value))
    return int(clean_str) if clean_str else np.nan

 
for col in ['Price', 'Old Price', 'Saving(rs)']:
    df[col] = df[col].apply(clean_currency)
In[10]:
df['Discount(%)'] = df['Discount(%)'].astype(str).str.extract(r'(\d+)').astype(float) #removeing %
In[11]:
 df['RAM_GB'] = df['RAM'].astype(str).str.extract(r'(\d+)').astype(float)
In[12]:
def clean_rom(value):
    # Handle NaN or already numeric values early
    if pd.isna(value):
        return np.nan
    
    # Force value to string and uppercase for consistent checking
    val = str(value).upper()
    
    # Use regex to find the numeric part
    numbers = re.findall(r'\d+', val)
    if not numbers:
        return np.nan
    
    numeric_val = float(numbers[0])
    
    # Convert TB to GB
    if 'TB' in val:
        return numeric_val * 1024
    return numeric_val

# Apply the function
df['ROM_GB'] = df['ROM'].apply(clean_rom)
In[13]:
# Convert to string first, then replace, then convert to float
df['Weight(KG)'] = df['Weight(KG)'].astype(str).str.replace('KG', '', case=False).astype(float)

Filling missing values

In[19]:
# List of numerical columns with nulls
num_cols = ['Processor', 'Screen Size', 'Weight(KG)', 'Price', 'Old Price', 'Saving(rs)', 'Discount(%)']

# Fill numerical nulls with the median
for col in num_cols:
    if df[col].dtype != 'object':
        df[col] = df[col].fillna(df[col].median())
In[20]:
# Fill Processor and Color with the most common value
df['Processor'] = df['Processor'].fillna(df['Processor'].mode()[0])
df['Color'] = df['Color'].fillna(df['Color'].mode()[0])
In[21]:
# Specifically fill RAM and ROM nulls with the most common configuration (e.g., 8GB or 16GB)
df['RAM_GB'] = df['RAM_GB'].fillna(df['RAM_GB'].mode()[0])
df['ROM_GB'] = df['ROM_GB'].fillna(df['ROM_GB'].mode()[0])

# Convert them to Int64 now that nulls are gone  
df['RAM_GB'] = df['RAM_GB'].astype(int)
df['ROM_GB'] = df['ROM_GB'].astype(int)

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# 1. Clean the 'Brand' column (fix the 'Acer' vs 'acer' issue)
df['Brand'] = df['Brand'].str.upper()

# 2. Set the aesthetic style
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")

# --- Visualization A: Boxplot (Best for Price Distribution) ---
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.boxplot(x='RAM_GB', y='Price', data=df, palette='viridis')
plt.title('Price Distribution by RAM Capacity', fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel('RAM (GB)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Price', fontsize=12)
plt.show()

# --- Visualization B: Faceted Regression (Best for Brand Comparison) ---
# This creates a separate small graph for each major brand to avoid overlap
top_brands = df['Brand'].value_counts().nlargest(6).index
df_top = df[df['Brand'].isin(top_brands)]

g = sns.lmplot(
    data=df_top, x="RAM_GB", y="Price", col="Brand", 
    hue="Brand", col_wrap=3, height=4, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.5}
)
g.set_axis_labels("RAM (GB)", "Price")
g.fig.suptitle('Price vs RAM Trends by Top Brands', y=1.05, fontsize=16)
plt.show()

top_10_colors = df['Color'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index.tolist()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# 1. DEFINE THE LOGIC (Re-creating the missing columns)
def score_processor(proc):
    proc = str(proc).upper()
    if 'M4' in proc or 'RYZEN 7' in proc or 'I7' in proc: return 10
    if 'RYZEN 5' in proc or 'I5' in proc: return 7
    if 'RYZEN 3' in proc or 'I3' in proc: return 4
    return 2

# 2. APPLY THE LOGIC (This creates the 'Processor_Score' column you were missing)
df['Processor_Score'] = df['Processor'].apply(score_processor)

# 3. CALCULATE PERFORMANCE & VFM
df['Enhanced_Performance'] = (df['RAM_GB'] * 0.4) + (df['Processor_Score'] * 4) + (df['ROM_GB'] / 128)
df['Business_VFM'] = (df['Enhanced_Performance'] / df['Price']) * 10000

# 4. FILTER FOR TOP 5
power_users = df[(df['RAM_GB'] >= 16) & (df['Processor_Score'] >= 7)]
power_picks = power_users.sort_values(by='Business_VFM', ascending=False).head(5)

# 5. CREATE THE VISUAL
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
ax = sns.barplot(x='Business_VFM', y='Model', data=power_picks, palette='viridis')

# Add Price labels on the bars for extra detail
for i, price in enumerate(power_picks['Price']):
    ax.text(0.1, i, f' Price: {price:,.0f}', va='center', color='white', fontweight='bold')

plt.title('Top 5 Power User Laptops (Best Value for Money)', fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel('Value Score')
plt.ylabel('Laptop Model')
plt.show()

VFM Score,Category,Business Meaning

  • 9.0 - 10.0 --> Excellent,High-end specs at a budget price; likely a massive discount.
  • 7.0 - 8.9 --> Great,Solid hardware for a very fair market price.
  • 5.0 - 6.9 --> Average,Standard pricing; you get exactly what you pay for.
  • Below 5.0 --> Premium,"You are paying for the Brand name, build quality, or thinness."

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# 1. Clean the data (fill missing values with 0 so the math works)
df['Discount(%)'] = df['Discount(%)'].fillna(0)
df['RAM_GB'] = df['RAM_GB'].fillna(8)  # Assume 8GB if missing
df['ROM_GB'] = df['ROM_GB'].fillna(256) # Assume 256GB if missing

# 2. Calculate a balanced VFM Score (0 to 10 scale)
# This formula gives points for Discount, RAM, and Storage
df['VFM_Score'] = (df['Discount(%)'] * 0.15) + (df['RAM_GB'] * 0.2) + (df['ROM_GB'] * 0.004)

# 3. Define the categories based on YOUR specific ranges
def get_category(score):
    if score >= 9.0:
        return 'Excellent'
    elif score >= 7.0:
        return 'Great'
    elif score >= 5.0:
        return 'Average'
    else:
        return 'Premium'

# Apply the categories to a new column
df['VFM_Category'] = df['VFM_Score'].apply(get_category)

# 4. Count the results and sort them in order
# We use 'reindex' to make sure the bars appear in order of quality
order = ['Excellent', 'Great', 'Average', 'Premium']
category_counts = df['VFM_Category'].value_counts().reindex(order).fillna(0)

# 5. Create the Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
colors = ['#2ecc71', '#27ae60', '#f1c40f', '#e74c3c'] # Green, Dark Green, Yellow, Red

category_counts.plot(kind='bar', color=colors, edgecolor='black')

# Add labels and titles
plt.title('Laptop Distribution by Value For Money (VFM)', fontsize=15, pad=20)
plt.xlabel('VFM Category', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Number of Laptops', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)

# Optional: Add the business meanings as text on the plot
plt.text(0, category_counts.max()*0.9, "High-end specs / Massive discount", fontsize=8, ha='center')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Assumptions

Null Hypothesis (H0): The average price is the same for all brands. (Brand doesn't matter).

Alternative Hypothesis (H1): At least one brand has a significantly different average price compared to the others

In[48]:
# Only includeing brands with more than one laptop for valid statistics
brand_counts = df['Brand'].value_counts()
valid_brands = brand_counts[brand_counts > 1].index
df_filtered = df[df['Brand'].isin(valid_brands)]

# Create groups of prices for each brand
brand_groups = [df_filtered[df_filtered['Brand'] == brand]['Price'] for brand in valid_brands]

ANOVA Test

This calculates the F-statistic and the p-value.
In[49]:
# Perform One-Way ANOVA
f_stat, p_val = stats.f_oneway(*brand_groups)

print(f"F-statistic: {f_stat}")
print(f"p-value: {p_val}")

F-statistic: 18.435729091618313
p-value: 2.044798984906327e-24
Rule: If p < 0.05, we reject the Null Hypothesis.

  • Tested brand influence on laptop prices. +Performed One-Way ANOVA statistical analysis.

  • High F-score shows significant brand differences.

  • Near-zero p-value proves results are real.

  • Rejected Null Hypothesis; Brand name matters.

  • Statistical data confirms brand price variation.

  • Math proves brands charge premium prices.
